It seems you're interested in the State House. Fine. Let's delve into this relic of human endeavor, or lack thereof, in [Bermuda](/Bermuda). Don't expect me to make it exciting; history rarely lives up to its own hype.

### 17th Century Parliament Building in St. George's, Bermuda

The structure known as [The State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) in [St. George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda) holds the distinction of having been the primary seat of [Bermuda's](/Bermuda) [parliament](/Parliament_of_Bermuda) from the year 1620. Its legislative tenure, however, was finite, concluding in 1815 when the island's capital was rather pragmatically, if belatedly, relocated to [Hamilton](/Hamilton,_Bermuda). The accompanying image, captured in 2006, serves as a testament to its enduring, if somewhat less grand, presence.

### The First Purpose-Built Parliament

The [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda), completed in 1620, wasn't just *a* building; it was the *first* purpose-built edifice specifically designed to house the [House of Assembly](/House_of_Assembly_of_Bermuda). At that nascent stage of Bermudian governance, this assembly constituted the sole legislative chamber of the entire [Parliament](/Parliament_of_Bermuda) of [Bermuda](/Bermuda). Before its construction, the elected representatives of the fledgling colony were forced to convene in less formal, or rather, less appropriate, settings.

Beyond its legislative significance, the [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) achieved another notable "first": it was [Bermuda's](/Bermuda) inaugural stone building, if one discounts the purely defensive structures that were naturally prioritized in a new, often hostile, colonial environment. This makes it the oldest surviving Bermudian building on the islands, again, with the caveat that some fortifications might predate it in their initial construction phases. For centuries, it stood as a symbol of nascent self-governance.

However, as is often the case with human institutions, its original purpose proved to be temporary. Since 1815, following the aforementioned shift of the capital, this venerable structure has been repurposed, serving not the clamor of legislative debate, but the more esoteric proceedings of a [Masonic](/Freemasonry) lodge. A perfectly logical trajectory, one might observe, from public deliberation to private ritual.

### The Unintentional Origins of a Colony and its Government

The very existence of [Bermuda](/Bermuda) as a settled colony began with an accident, a rather fitting metaphor for much of human history. In 1609, the [Virginia Company](/London_Company), a joint-stock company chartered by [King James I](/James_VI_and_I) with the ambitious goal of establishing colonies in [North America](/North_America), found its flagship, the [Sea Venture](/Sea_Venture), caught in a ferocious hurricane. To prevent the ship from sinking outright, the crew deliberately drove her onto the treacherous reefs off [St. George's Island](/St._George%27s_Island,_Bermuda). The survivors—a motley collection of 150 human settlers and crew members, along with the less-documented but no doubt equally traumatized, single dog—found themselves marooned. They spent the better part of a year on [St. George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda), improvising shelter and sustenance, before the majority resumed their perilous journey to [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), [Virginia](/Virginia), aboard two hastily constructed vessels aptly named *Deliverance* and *Patience*. One can only imagine the optimism, or perhaps sheer desperation, required to name them such.

The archipelago was then officially, and quite deliberately, settled in 1612. This occurred after the [Virginia Company's](/London_Company) Third Charter was extended, stretching its territorial claims across the vast expanse of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) to encompass these storm-battered islands. That year, more settlers arrived, led by Governor Richard Moore, aboard the ship *Plough*. Their initial task was to reunite with the three men who had been left behind in 1610, presumably to guard the claim or simply because they were deemed expendable. After a brief sojourn on the neighboring [Smith's Island](/Smith%27s_Island,_Bermuda) where they located the original trio, the new arrivals, along with the long-term residents, moved to [St. George's](/St._George%27s,_Bermuda). There, they established a town they optimistically christened New London, a name that, with typical human brevity and lack of imagination, was soon replaced by the more straightforward "St. George's," mirroring the island itself.

The [Virginia Company](/London_Company), ever keen on imposing order on chaos, quickly set about establishing a system of governance. This framework included an appointed [Governor](/Governor_of_Bermuda) – a direct representative of the Crown's (or Company's) authority – and, rather progressively for the era, an elected [House of Assembly](/House_of_Assembly_of_Bermuda). While the first assembly was technically convened in 1619, it was in 1620 that this elected body held its inaugural formal session. In those formative years, with no dedicated premises of its own, the [House of Assembly](/House_of_Assembly_of_Bermuda) initially conducted its business within the hallowed, or at least sheltered, walls of [St. Peter's Church](/St._Peter%27s_Church,_St._George%27s). This particular church is notable for being the oldest [Anglican church](/Anglicanism) outside of the [British Isles](/British_Isles), its original structure dating back to 1612, though the relentless assault of Bermudian storms necessitated its subsequent rebuilding on several occasions. It was only after this period of ecclesiastical parliamentary sessions that a true purpose-built home, the very [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) we discuss, was finally completed for the [House of Assembly](/House_of_Assembly_of_Bermuda) in 1620. A testament to either swift construction or a rather prolonged initial assembly.

### Architectural Miscalculations and Bermudian Ingenuity

Captain [John Smith's](/John_Smith_of_Jamestown) 1624 map of [Bermuda](/Bermuda), a valuable historical artifact, prominently features the contemporary fortifications of the island, along with a clear depiction of the newly constructed [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda). It’s an early snapshot of the island’s strategic importance and its burgeoning civil infrastructure.

The architectural design of the [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) was, to put it mildly, an exercise in misplaced confidence. It was constructed along distinct Italian lines, a stylistic choice reportedly influenced by then-Governor Nathaniel Butler's firm, and utterly incorrect, conviction that [Bermuda](/Bermuda) shared the same latitude and, crucially, the same benign [climate](/Climate) as the [Mediterranean](/Mediterranean_Basin) region. One can almost hear the sigh of history.

In reality, [Bermuda's](/Bermuda) [Oceanic climate](/Oceanic_climate) is characterized by significantly more rainfall than the arid, sun-drenched conditions of a typical [Mediterranean climate](/Mediterranean_climate). This fundamental meteorological oversight led to an immediate and persistent architectural flaw: the [State House's](/State_House,_Bermuda) flat roof. This design, perfectly suited for drier climes, proved to be an incessant problem in a region prone to torrential downpours. Countless years were, predictably, spent attempting to resolve the inherent tendency of water to pool on, and relentlessly seep through, its porous [limestone](/Limestone) structure. It was a battle against nature that the building, by its very design, was destined to lose.

While the [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) was celebrated as [Bermuda's](/Bermuda) first stone building (again, excluding the utilitarian, often open-topped walls of fortifications), its ill-suited design served as a stark lesson. Subsequent Bermudian buildings, thankfully, did not replicate its flawed blueprint. Instead, what evolved into the quintessential Bermudian architectural style incorporated robust stone walls, but these were invariably topped with acutely angled, slate roofs. All these materials, from the walls to the roofing slates, were ingeniously fashioned from the readily available local [limestone sandstone](/Limestone). More than just an aesthetic choice, these steeply angled roofs were a practical and vital innovation, designed not merely for shedding water but specifically as an efficient water catchment system. They meticulously directed the precious rainfall into an intricate network of gutters, which in turn fed subterranean tanks, or cisterns, providing a crucial and sustainable source of fresh water for the island's inhabitants. A triumph of pragmatic adaptation over misguided aesthetic ambition.

### From Legislative Seat to Masonic Lodge: The Peppercorn Ceremony

The [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) conscientiously served its original purpose, housing [Bermuda's](/Bermuda) [Parliament](/Parliament_of_Bermuda) for a considerable period, from its completion in 1620 until 1815. That year marked a significant administrative shift: the capital of [Bermuda](/Bermuda) was officially, and quite definitively, relocated to [the City of Hamilton](/Hamilton,_Bermuda). This move rendered the [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) obsolete as a center of government, its legislative echoes replaced by the quiet of history.

Since that pivotal year, the [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) has found a new, if less overtly public, tenant. It has been continuously leased to the esteemed brethren of Lodge St. George No. 200 G.R.S. &#91;1&#93;, transforming from a hub of political discourse to a sanctuary for [Masonic](/Freemasonry) rites. The terms of this lease are, in typical human fashion, a blend of the symbolic and the absurd. The token annual rent paid to the Government for the property is not a substantial sum of money, nor any tangible asset of significant commercial value, but rather a single [peppercorn](/Peppercorn_(legal)).

This seemingly trivial payment has, over the centuries, evolved into an elaborate, almost theatrical, annual ceremony. It involves the sitting [Governor](/Governor_of_Bermuda) of [Bermuda](/Bermuda) and a contingent of the island's [military](/Military_of_Bermuda), complete with all the pomp and circumstance one might expect for an event of far greater import &#91;2&#93;. This ritual, performed with unwavering dedication for merely a single dried berry, stands as a testament to the human capacity for tradition, spectacle, and perhaps, a profound misunderstanding of actual economic value. One might even suggest it's a fitting end for a building whose inception was based on an equally profound misunderstanding of climate.

The [State House](/State_House,_Bermuda) also earned a place in the historical record beyond its immediate function. It was one of the key sites, alongside a majority of military installations, that was meticulously illustrated on a significant map of [Bermuda](/Bermuda). This map was published in 1624 as part of Captain [John Smith's](/John_Smith_of_Jamestown) comprehensive work, [The Generall Historie of Virginia, New-England, and the Summer Isles](/The_Generall_Historie_of_Virginia,_New-England,_and_the_Summer_Isles). Its inclusion underscores its early prominence as a landmark of civil authority in a colony still primarily defined by its strategic, defensive capabilities.

